voice_to_text: Everything could have been avoided had the rest of the straw hats been present during the Marine. So we're talking about if the straw hats were at Marine for, would things have gone differently? Absolutely not. They would have gone way worse. The question you have to ask here is, how strong were the Straw Hats? And who is the strongest Straw Hat on the crew at this point in time? It's obviously Luffy. It's always gonna be Luffy. And Luffy didn't stand a damn chance against the vast majority of people on the playing field of Marine Fort. So if we included all the rest of the Straw Hats, what would have really happened? First off, we obviously needed Marine Ford for Luffy's development. Everything that happened with ace help push Luffy to become stronger. This entire thing was to let Luffy know that, hey, bro, you are not strong enough for what you're going up against. When you get to the New World, it's a whole new level, man. These emperors are something different. If Luffy didn't stand a chance there, the rest of his team didn't. And honest to god, the same thing would have happened. Ace would have gotten god. But the problem is, all of the Straw Hats would have been caught up in the fight and wouldn't have been able to escape. The fact that Luffy was able to quickly escape on LAW ship was super, super lucky. But again, LAW wouldn't have been Able to get all the Straw Hats out, or they wouldn't have been able to survive on their own ship to get all the way out. There's just no chance they would have done any good work there. It. It would have been dark, so. Yeah. Um. Why weren't the Straw Hats there? Because they didn't need to be there. We needed the story to be able to move forward. If they were there, one piece would be over, and someone else would be king of the Pirates.

voice_to_text: You gotta stop telling people to start with attack on Titan. Like as a first starter anime. I'm a double down on this because she is absolutely right. She spoke no lies. When you introduce somebody into anime who's never seen anime before, do not start with attack on Titan. Because after they finish attack on Titan they're gonna think the next animes after are gonna be peak or ass peak as attack on Titan. Which is false. Hell, I'll even say this don't even start with the sinister six or aka the new gen animes as your first animes. Black Clover, Demon Slayer, Chainsaw Man, Fire Force, JJK, and My Hero Academia. Some of those animes are interchangeable depending on your opinions, but I know I would not tell somebody to start watching those as their first animes because a lot of it is bad shit. Wild, she mentioned Death Note as a first anime. I approve. I approve of that. This nigga had me weak the entire anime. Buddy was chilling the entire time with all the BS. Was going bro this man had me weak and I love Ryuk and the OG himself l this dude was fucking intelligent the entire anime. I love him so much. One thing she should have mentioned is everybody's taste in anime is like a movie. Movies have different genres, animes have different genres. So I always ask a person when they're coming into anime what genre of movie do you Like and if you can name me the genre movie then I can start. Maybe recommend the types of animes you might like. Another thing to mention is also the big three. Unless they're willing to watch 300+ episodes of an anime, let them do it. But don't recommend Naruto, Dragon Ball, one piece and all them other ones. Don't even mention those because they got a suit through that BS. Like how the OG anime watchers did back then. Another thing you had to realize is that not every newcomer to anime is gonna fuck with shonen. They're not, cause not everybody is for shonen. That's why it is important to ask the new person to anime what type of genre of movies do they prefer? Now, if they like romance movies, okay, you can recommend that. But if they ask something outside of romance movies, okay, well then you can introduce them to other forms of or other genres of anime that they might take a liking to. But that's just, you know. I would say a safe way of them not to abandon anime. Because a lot of new anime comers think that oh, it's all about screaming, fighting, blood and all that, all the crap. Which is not the case.

Question of the anime variety do you think the overpowered MC trope has its place in anime? Go back and watch original video cause he makes some really good talking points about how the overpowered MC trope isn't really as well written anymore. Or well really ever. It has some situations, but it's just. It's a loss. It's a lot in anime to write overpowered MC trope. Well I wanna make my own points about this cause I feel like there are some characters who have their overpowered MC trope written with y'all. I have an example of this as well Sid. Now while you may disagree, Sid in eminence and shadow is an overpowered character done really well. Because the whole goal of the anime is that there are people who are not able to compete with him on a power level. But there are people who are sort of tarnishing his own name or the name of the name of his group. And they like, they don't tackle him head on, they find ways around him. They see, they show him as kind of a strategy. A really overpowered main character, don't get me wrong, but like, they don't. They show him as no power main character, but they also show that there's stuff he can't do with as well as quickly. Like if a group is tarnishing his name, he has to go out of his way to find them, and that might take a couple episodes. Also, another thing with him is that he isn't. He doesn't want to be the main character in his own show. He wants to be the side character, at least for Season 1. And that's something that he struggles with, is that he's kind of being pushed into the light while he wants to remain in the shadow. Pun intended. But that's just one example. I could. I have, like, a handful more of these, like again to. But I'm not going to for the sake of. I don't want this video to go to like 5 minutes long.

voice_to_text: Is Demon Slayer carried by its animation? I mean, the simple answer is no. In my opinion, Demon Slayer just can't be carried by animation. Don't get me wrong, the animation is very good, but I don't think is what makes the show enjoyable. You could have the worst storyline and the worst characters, the worst voice acting. And just because the animation is good, it doesn't mean people are gonna watch it. So first of all, is the voice acting the voice acting? Demon slayer sub all dub is fucking brilliant. And the people who think you know it is carried by animation, you gotta give it credit for that. The only reason why they don't like it is because at the end of every story, the end of every demon, there's some long fucking monologue about how he's actually a good guy or how he's redeemed himself or something. So it feels same after like 4 demons. The other thing to do is about the music design. The sound effect designs every sort of fight or battle leaving conversation. The sound is perfect. Whoever's a sound engineer on that is doing a wicked job. It's like a broad in Japan said. He said sound design is one of the most important things when creating a video. So when you create a TV show, anime or whatever, sound design can actually carry the scene. Freer nailed it as well. But I can understand what people are saying about Demon Slayer getting carried by animation. Also we gotta think of is the horny weebs who literally sit there and every time a Hashira comes up, they're like, oh, my God, she's so pretty. And if you seen the Soul Smith arc, then we all know, you know, the Hashira. And that just had the boobs out all the time. That was it. She was kinda cool, kinda useful, but that's all she did, right? Every sort of joke or gag was anything to do with that. So that's probably where most of the audience for Demon Slayer lies. voice_to_text: I just wanted to make a quick follow-up video to say I officially graduated today as valedictorian of my college class! Now that I've officially graduated, I wanted to share my Persona 5 inspired valedictorian speech. Here it goes: I'm honoured to have been chosen as a valedictorian of this year's graduating class. My name is Raven and I am a Secondary Education and English major with double minors in Art and Writing. In true English major fashion, on my graduation cap I've written a quote from one of my favourite characters of all time, “I will carve my own path for myself.” We've all likely encountered individuals who entrust others with their destinies to such an extent that they unconsciously relinquish some of their freedoms in the process. Perhaps, we've been in that position ourselves, seeking external guidance to fulfill others’ ideas of happiness in the hope that that happiness will become our own. However, genuine growth and happiness emerge from following our inner compass and forging paths aligned with our deepest aspirations. I am the eldest daughter of immigrants. I am a first generation college student. I am an English major, even though English is not my first language. Despite encountering skepticism about my potential for success, I have remained steadfast in my self-belief and identity. Of course, there are times when relying on and trusting others is essential. I could not have overcome the numerous linguistic and societal barriers I faced because of my background alone. However, the pivotal decisions, born of my free will, forged a path I proudly tread alongside you all as fellow graduates. Trust is a precious gift—to ourselves as much as others. Embracing challenges fosters growth, yet surrendering crucial decisions to external forces only hinders true happiness and self-pride. “What's a life worth in a reality that was cooked up just to satisfy someone else?” “I say ‘none.’” Your happiness and development rest solely in your hands. Carve your own path for yourself, drawing upon the skills and knowledge that have been infused in our education by our founders to shape a narrative you can be proud of. To anyone graduating this season, congratulations class of 2024!

voice_to_text: Endeavor so doesn't get a redemption arc. Like, he just doesn't deserve one. Oh, god. Well, then it's a good thing that the point of his character is that he is not getting redemption. Yes, to us it is a redemption arc. Because we in our world see our character goes from bad to good. They have a redemption arc. But what endeavor is getting is not redemption. It. It is atonement. And he acknowledges this within the sea, where Koshi makes it very clear. Endeavor knows he cannot be forgiven. He knows the acts he has done are beyond forgiveness. And the point of Endeavor's character is not at all to be forgiven. Cause again, it is acknowledged within the series that he can't be forgiven. He is beyond forgiveness. But the point of his character is to show atonement. To show that someone who has done something terrible can continue to live on. And even if they're not forgiven, they can seek to be better and do better. Not to get forgiveness, but to make up for the past. To try to atone for their sins. And even if they're not forgiven, at least they're doing something to be better. And that's the point of Endeavor's character. That's why Horikoshi hasn't killed him off. Horikoshi has had plenty of opportunities where he could have killed him off, but he's still kicking. Because the point of his character is to live and to see the future and to help The future heroes be better. To make sure that there's never another endeavor. That's the point of this character. Not to be forgiven, but to atone and to help make the future better.

voice_to_text: Kind of overwhelm the audience. You can burn people out, and that's not always the best approach. This creator is talking about one piece currently having an ongoing manga, anime, and live action series. It getting a anime remake might be a little bit too much and might burn out the audience for one piece. I disagree with this take because of one very specific reason. All of these sources for one piece are targeting a relatively different demographic. You've got people who are die hard anime fans. They've been watching the one piece anime since 1999, and they are watching it every single week. You also have people who are manga fans who prefer to consume this kind of content in a manga format. And on top of that, the live action just brought in a massive demographic that has been very averse to starting the anime or the manga because of how long they are. All of these formats do a fantastic job of telling this amazing story that we love to an audience that wouldn't normally consume it otherwise. I would say the number one barrier to get anybody into the one piece anime or manga is because it's too long and the pacing is rough. And for current anime and manga readers, it's way off the base for what they're used to consuming. So I think getting a remake gives one piece another amazing chance to get deep into the hearts of the newer anime and Manga fan base so do I think this is gonna cause burnout? No, another side of this is one piece fans or one piece fans. They're gonna consume it in all possible facets. Once I catch up on the one piece anime, I'm sure I'm gonna be jumping over the manga to consume more content. And I'm gonna watch season 2 of the live action the moment it drops cause I'm super excited about that too because again, I love one piece. And finally when they do remake the anime, I'm gonna be watching that as well. I'm hyped for it. I do not think this is gonna cause fatigue because I think the people who like one piece in their certain forms will continue consuming it that way. And this is just gonna grow the fan base even bigger.

voice_to_text: online can't seem to decide on whether or not women fetishizing gay men is a bad thing so I am a gay man and I have a lot of things to say about this whole uh fujoshi situation so for those of you who don't know the term fujoshi is Japanese in origin it originates off of this Japanese forum website called 2channel um fujoshi itself is a pun on a Japanese term for a proper woman and it instead means “rotten woman” and this is rotten in the sense of like the classical definition of rotten like decayed spoiled stuff like that and this was a term used largely by men to refer to women in fandom spaces um who would typically do things that they didn't like such as you know shipping characters in general or whatever else but notably it was not a term that exclusively referred to women who enjoyed the boys love genre and the reason that these women are called rotten specifically was because in Japanese society there is an expectation that in a woman's life at some point she will leave behind the things of uh the things of her childhood and such and uh you know begin to focus on adult life and being and like being the mother of the family and these women were called rotten because they had “spoiled” themselves by either making themselves quotes around this by “making themselves undesirable to men”  or, in the case of ones who were married, “shaming their families and husbands” and such and so uh this term was eventually reclaimed by women in these fandom spaces like uh oh you're saying that I'm rotten well I'll be as rotten as I want to be and they began self identifying as fujoshi and so uh what people in uh western spaces have done is take a derogatory term that was reclaimed by the people it was used against and using it as a derogatory term again so a lot of people are using the language of gay liberation to be misogynistic because fujoshi began as a misogynistic term and frankly which, of these sounds more homophobic to you? is it A: there are women who consume media about gay men and like it or B: gay men are endangered and need to be protected from the scary straight women like one of those sounds far more homophobic to me than the other additionally to ignore the effect that the anti fujoshi “movement” I guess you'd say has had on gay trans men would be at best naive and at worst outright malicious like uh the amount of people who will say “oh,” “these are just straight women…” “…pretending to be gay men to infiltrate gay male spaces to get with gay men…” “because they fetishize them.” like, if you switch the genders around then like that's basically just classic transphobic rhetoric like there is no way around it and that's not to say that uh all anti fujoshi people are transphobes um there are definitely transphobic people mostly TERFs who who will pedal this uh pedal this narrative of straight women uh attempting to fetishize gay men and then there are people who otherwise like would not hold a lot of transphobic views hearing that and thinking “oh…” “…I don't like gay men being fetishized…” “…so I'm also against fujoshis” and just agreeing that without any um are at agreeing with it at face value so the ultimate takeaway to this is that whenever you hear about a group of people um do your own research like look into them from sources that are not just TikTok videos uh yeah

voice_to_text: If Krillin was on earth, would he have stopped Omni Man? Oh my goodness, let's. Let's. No exaggeration, you would likely need at most Namics Saga Krillin if an absolute most android to sell Saga Krillin to defeat the likes of Omni Man. And the only reason I'm pushing that far into the series is for the speed, because we know that Omni Man's like best feats are his speed feats. Because strength wise, him and two other viltrumites were needed to destroy a destabilized planet, which puts him comfortably around like continental to multi continental in terms of power. But even if we highballed him and said that he could have destroyed a planet viltrum by himself and put him at planetary, that would still put him at like Raditz level. And that's crazy because by the Namek saga Krillin's power level was already like 50 times higher than Raditz. So me pushing to Namek Saga or further isn't to deal strength wise with Omni Man, it's more so to deal with his speed. Because speed is gonna be the only thing in Omni Man's favor up until a certain point in the Dragon Ball series. Because strength wise and durability wise he doesn't stand up to even Namik Saga or Android Saga Krillin in terms of power, let alone if we are using current Krillin like tournament of power or even Moral Arc or later Krillin. Ironically, Krillin flicks Omni Man's head off. Especially if this is like A bloodlusted thing where Krillin is for some reason going for the kill. Even Omni Man speed would be nothing compared to current Krillin. Even when he was sparring against base Goku and we knew base Goku was more than likely holding back. It doesn't matter how much he's holding back, that is still Goku. The fact that Krillin could even make a suppressed Goku fight back properly is a feat in itself. And let's just say for the sake of argument, we made their stats equal. I'd still bet on Krillin because he is a better fighter. So even an equal stats match up where everything is equalized. I'd still say Krillin because he just has the ability to fight properly, whereas Omni Man isn't as skilled of a fighter. But yeah, at any normal circumstance, anything past the Namek Saga's overkill.

Très bonne vidéo de levarant qui nous montre 1 case de marie-joie dans laquelle on voit 1 phare. Il rappelle aussi que marie-joie s'est située à 10.000m d'altitude, donc sur headline, et il se questionne sur la pertinence qu'il y a 1 phare aussi haut dans le ciel. Il nous donne sa théorie selon laquelle les dragons célestes auraient placé 1 phare à cette altitude en prévision de la montée des eaux. Car oui, dans le dernier chapitre, et attention au spoil, Vega punk nous dit que le monde va sombrer sous les eaux, laissant penser que l'eau va continuer à monter et peut-être jusqu'à 10.000m d'altitude, c'est-à-dire jusqu'à redline. En vrai c'est 1 bonne théorie, j'aime beaucoup. Par contre, moi en voyant ça, j'ai pensé à autre chose. Suite au dernier chapitre, je vous ai déjà parlé de la théorie selon laquelle peut-être que 1 fois que l'eau sera montée, les dragons célestes partiront tout simplement vers la lune. Et moi je me pose la question, est-ce que ce phare, il serait pas là justement pour ça ? Qui nous dit que les dragons célestes ils ont pas déjà construit des bateaux volants pour faire des tests pour essayer d'aller jusqu'à la lune ? Et donc du coup, bah ce phare qui est placé tout en haut de Red Line, il serait là pour guider les bateaux volants des dragons célestes ? C'est dingue, pour pas qu'ils se perdent au milieu des nuages et cetera. Ce serait pas fou les gars parce Que oui, 1 phare de base c'est là pour guider les bateaux pour pas qu'il se prenne des montagnes et cetera. Donc ce phare, s'il est placé là, peut-être que c'est pour aider les bateaux volants tout simplement. Bref voilà les gars, je sais pas ce que vous pensez de ma petite théorie, honnêtement je la trouve pas mieux que celle de levarant, juste elle est différente. Donc dites-moi ce que vous en pensez. Vous êtes plutôt team levarant ou team guiki ? Dans la bonne humeur et la bonne ambiance d'ailleurs allez follow le varan, il fait du contenu de qualité et d'ailleurs je sais pas si vous avez vu mais il a gagné, euh. Le jeu du mon corveau là qui veut gagner des Berry ! Incroyable ! Ce mec est 1 monstre de connaissance en One Piece, bien plus que moi d'ailleurs ! Donc allez le follow

voice_to_text: What's an anime rule you'll break? I have a couple that I know for a fact I would absolutely break. First off, if I get even the slightest hint that an ally, or hell, even someone I met just once even has a hint of evil or a hint of becoming evil, I'm gonna do one of two things. Both involve my fist in their face. I'm either going to knock some sense into them or knock them six feet under. Whichever happens first. I am not dealing with a possible major threat, especially if they are like a lead supporting character, because that means their power would actually be a threat if they were allowed to actually go far. So either punch them repeatedly until they've just get those thoughts out of their head, or keep going until there's no possible chance they could become a threat because they're going to be buried and the next thing. I am not respecting one V ones. I don't care if you're even slightly stronger than me, or hell, even if we're equal in power, I am bringing every ally I have. Hell, I'll bring the damn sensei character and we're jumping you if you pose any sort of threat to the world. especially if you're a threat to multiple people or the world at large. We are not respecting one v ones. I am not pulling some modern JJK where they are just fighting 1 v 1 when most of The series, they jumped people. If you are a genuine threat, don't expect to be 1 v 1. And lastly, I'm gonna do kind of a. I guess you could say this is a disrespectful thing. I will say the name of one attack just to hit you with a different one. One, it catches you off guard. 2 it makes me less predictable. And 3, it's just gonna be something that most characters don't do. Oh, and on top of that, I'm not gonna just declare what attack I'm directly gonna be throwing. I'm not gonna be charging like a Kamehameha or a Rasengan. Because then they hear what is gonna be coming at them. I'm gonna leave them on their toes, not knowing what they're gonna get hit by. Or if I really wanna throw them off, say the name of the attack that they think they're gonna get hit by and try to prepare for that. When in reality, I have something entirely different being cooked up to throw right at them.
